				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf content is still king in a media business challenged by new technologies and nimble upstarts, Rupert Murdoch hungers to wear the crown,â <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/rupert-murdoch-said-to-have-made-offer-for-time-warner/?ref=media">Andrew Ross Sorkin and Michael J. de la Merced write in DealBook</a></b>. On Wednesday, Mr. Murdochâs <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/looking-back-on-a-decade-of-murdoch-deals">boldest bid yet</a></b> emerged: an $80 billion takeover offer for Time Warner Inc., which would be the biggest media deal in more than a decade. Time Warner has rebuffed his offer and no talks are underway. But Mr. Murdoch is known for getting what he wants â even when companies have first said no â and people briefed on the matter said he is unlikely to walk away anytime soon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Murdochâs pursuit is likely to <b>set off a wave of takeover battles</b> elsewhere in the industry as others race to keep up with the media mogul. âMr. Murdochâs 21st Century Fox is seeking to create a colossus in the television and film industries at a time when both face pressure from the growing power of cable companies like Comcast and online video giants like Google,â Mr. Sorkin and Mr. de la Merced write. Combining the two companies would bring under one roof some of the leading sources of content, including HBO and Fox Broadcasting. Notably, <b>the deal would not include CNN</b>, which 21st Century Fox plans to sell in any deal to assuage concerns from antitrust regulators.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">SIZE MATTERS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Looming large over all of the big media deals this year â both Comcast and AT&#038;T are pursuing enormous takeovers â is the competitive threat from Silicon Valley, with its technology behemoths like Facebook, Google and Amazon. âThe giant market capitalizations and market power residing in Silicon Valley have rippled into the rest of the economy,â <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/business/media/in-modern-media-realm-big-mergers-are-a-bulwark-against-rivals.html?ref=media">David Carr writes in the Media Equation column</a></b>. âThe people behind this sudden surge of proposed media mergers say they are only going on steroids to avoid getting sand kicked in their face by even bigger bullies in the technology world.â But beyond bigness, Mr. Carr adds, âthere is <b>no compelling logic driving a merger</b> of Time Warner and 21st Century Fox.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">COMBINING HOLLYWOOD STUDIOS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> In the bid, Mr. Murdoch is said to have made clear that his 21st Century Fox and Time Warnerâs Warner Bros., two of Hollywoodâs six major studios, would be managed jointly, but kept essentially separate, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/business/media/a-potential-combination-of-two-of-hollywoods-most-successful-studios.html?ref=media">Michael Cieply, Brooks Barnes and Bill Carter write in The New York Times</a></b>. âBut business history and market pressures in both the movie and television industries make it almost inevitable that studio overhead would be cut, back-office operations would be combined, and jobs would be eliminated if a merger happens.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BEHIND THE BID <span class="divider"> | </span></span> While the offer from 21st Century Fox may have been unsolicited and even unwanted, it nevertheless represented a validation of Jeff Bewkesâs stewardship of the company, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/business/media/foxs-bid-was-made-possible-by-time-warner-chiefs-revival-program.html?ref=media">Jonathan Mahler and Emily Steel write in The New York Times</a></b>. Since Mr. Bewkes took over as chief executive of Time Warner in 2008, he has carried out an ambitious turnaround strategy, methodically shedding Time Warnerâs noncore assets to transform the company from a sprawling media conglomerate into a pure entertainment entity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over the years, Mr. Bewkes has unloaded Time Warner Cable, AOL and, most recently, the publisher Time Inc., whose spinoff was completed last month. Wall Street has cheered his approach, but there are questions about whether it was Mr. Bewkesâs intention all along to make Time Warner an acquisition target. (To allay takeover concerns on Wednesday, Mr. Bewkes <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/to-reassure-time-warner-employees-bewkes-takes-to-the-small-screen">sent a short recorded video of himself</a></b> to his employees, emphasizing that Time Warner had rejected 21st Century Foxâs bid.)</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">From Bloomberg View <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b><a href="//www.bloombergview.com/articles/2014-07-16/fox-and-time-warner-need-each-other">Susan Crawford writes</a></b>: âIn 2010, Gary Shteyngartâs âSuper Sad True Love Storyâ amused readers with its futuristic depiction of people traveling via UnitedContinentalDeltamerican and banking with AlliedWasteCVSCitigroupCredit. In Shteyngartâs imagination, only two television channels provided all âMediaâ: Fox Liberty-Prime and Fox Liberty-Ultra. The merger of Time Warner Inc. and 21st Century Fox, apparently suggested by Rupert Murdoch last month, shows <b>Shteyngart was only barely ahead of his time</b>.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BANK OF AMERICA SETTLEMENT TALKS HIT SNAG <span class="divider"> | </span></span> After months of negotiations, a possible settlement between Bank of America and the Justice Department is in jeopardy over a disagreement on the bankâs liability for the suspected mortgage misdeeds of its Countrywide Financial and Merrill Lynch units, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/bank-of-america-earnings-slump-43/">Michael Corkery writes in DealBook</a></b>. On Tuesday, the bankâs lawyers met in Washington with prosecutors from the Justice Department, but the two sides remain far from reaching a deal. Federal prosecutors are said to have left the meeting planning to move ahead with a suit.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>A major sticking point</b> in the talks with the Justice Department is how much the bank should be penalized for mortgage securities sold by Countrywide. The bank has argued that in devising a penalty, prosecutors should take into account that Bank of America tried to back out of its purchase of Merrill, but felt pressured by regulators to go through with the acquisition in the depths of the financial crisis. <b>The two sides are also far apart on money</b>. The Justice Department had been seeking as much as $17 billion, but the bank is offering roughly $12 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Legal costs also dominated Bank of Americaâs second-quarter results on Wednesday, when the bank <b>reported profit of $2.3 billion</b>, dragged down 43 percent from the period a year earlier partly by $4 billion in legal expenses. It was the second consecutive quarter that the bank reported a large legal expense.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Monthly data on <b>housing starts</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. Weekly <b>jobless claims</b> are released at 8:30 a.m. <b>James B. Bullard</b>, president of the St. Louis Fed, gives a speech on the economy and monetary policy at the âOwensboro in 2065 Summitâ at 1:35 p.m. in Owensboro, Ken. <b>Morgan Stanley</b> reports second-quarter earnings before the market opens.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: The House Committee on Financial Services <b>Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade</b> holds a hearing titled âA Legislative Proposal Entitled the âBank Account Seizure of Terrorist Assets (Basta) Actââ at 9:45 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">TREASURY URGES END TO TAX INVERSIONS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Lawmakers say they want to stop United States companies from reincorporating overseas to lower their tax bills, but the Obama administration and Congress appear unlikely to take any action to halt these so-called inversions anytime soon, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/obama-administration-seeks-end-to-inversion-deals">DealBookâs David Gelles writes</a></b>. On Tuesday, Treasury Secretary Jacob J. Lew sent letters to the top members of the House Ways and Means Committee and Senate Finance Committee, urging Congress to take immediate action through broad corporate tax reform to halt the rush of companies abroad. Absent that, Mr. Lew encouraged congressional leaders to act before more companies made similar moves.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In his letter, Mr. Lew built on a proposal by Senator Ron Wyden, Democrat of Oregon and chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, that would <b>essentially ban inversions</b>, with an effective date of May of this year. Such a proposal would eliminate the tax benefits of any inversion deals that had not been completed by that date, which could potentially affect numerous announced transaction. Even <b>deals announced before May could be affected</b> because they have not yet closed. Still, the wave of inversions looks set to continue unabated as a partisan Congress remains gridlocked and companies rush to strike such deals while they still can.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
